#X text 441 49 Let's check the frequency response of [lop3~] below. You can click and drag in the upper gray area \, it acts as a slider. This example considers a sample rate of 44.1 Khz. Listen to the patch below \, where we filter a white noise source.;
#X obj 610 212 lop3~;
#X text 49 44 The [lop3~] from ELSE is yet another variant of [lop~] (and [lop2~] for that matter). More details and information on the math and implementation is provided on a further chapter for advanced filter theory. What we can say for now is that it also includes a two sample average that we've seen here before., f 52;
#X text 49 154 The filter also has a loss of 6 dB per octave \, but unlike [lop~] \, the behaviour does not change over 5 khz and it keeps the same low pass curve behaviour. You can have the same behaviour of a two sample average when the rolloff frequency reaches half the nyquist frequency., f 52;
#X connect 0 0 7 1;
#X connect 2 0 7 0;
#X connect 7 0 5 0;
